// For each pixel: bg[i] = alpha*frame[i] + (1-alpha)*bg[i]
// foreground_mask[i] = abs(frame[i] - bg[i]) > threshold
```

**Lucas-Kanade optical flow** — tracks a sparse set of good corners frame-to-frame using an image pyramid + least-squares patch matching. This is just 5×5 matrix solves per point — pure `float` arrays.

**Blob analysis** — connected-component labeling on the foreground mask to find bounding boxes, centroids, and silhouette dimensions. This is a classic union-find flood fill.

The output of your classical CV becomes the **input to your neural net**:
```
[cx, cy,          // blob centroid (normalized 0..1)
 bw, bh,          // bounding box size
 vx0..vxN,        // optical flow vectors for N tracked points
 vy0..vyN,
 aspect_ratio,    // shape hint
 motion_magnitude] // total movement energy